    "body": "### Problem\n\nCurrently, Neovim wraps lines visually at the edge of the window when `:set wrap` is enabled. However, there is no way to configure Neovim to wrap lines visually at a specific column, such as 100 columns, regardless of window width — and crucially, without inserting newlines or modifying buffer content.\n\nThis feature would allow users to:\n\n- Maintain clean file content (no auto-formatting or hard wraps)\n- Visually constrain content to a specific column limit\n- Work more comfortably with wide monitors or variable window widths\n- Use Neovim more like a traditional word processor or writing tool when desired\n\nWhile `colorcolumn=100` provides a visual guide, it doesn't help with actual line wrapping. The current workaround is to resize the window to 100 columns, but this is cumbersome, especially when working with multiple splits or varying screen sizes. Users may want to maintain a consistent soft wrap margin regardless of screen layout.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIntroduce a setting such as:\n\n```vim\n:set wrapcolumn=100\n```\nThis would:\n\n- Enable soft line wrapping (like `:set wrap`)\n- Wrap visually at column 100, regardless of actual window width\n- Not insert newlines or modify buffer text\n- Respect `linebreak`, `breakindent`, and `showbreak` for better readability\n\nThis is similar to Emacs’ `fill-column` + visual line mode, or soft wrap margins in many GUI editors.\n\n",
